#compdef pillar
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# pillar-markup/pillar src/Pillar-Cli/Clap*.class.st
# (**Pharo Smalltalk language**; uses **Clap** — Pharo's
# port of Rust's clap library; first documented Pharo
# Smalltalk CLI in the corpus):
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarCommand.class.st lines
#     18-44 (`commandSpecification` class-side method:
#     `(ClapCommandSpec id: #pillar) description: '...';
#     commandClass: self; addHelp; add: ((ClapFlag id:
#     #version) description: 'Prints the version of
#     your Pharo VM'); yourself.` followed by
#     `pillarCommandsList do: [ :each | command
#     addSubcommand: each ]` — Smalltalk MESSAGE-CHAIN
#     spec builder; subcommands auto-discovered via
#     `self allSubclasses select: [ :each | each
#     isAbstract not ]`)
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarArchetypeCommand.class.st
#     lines 16-29 (`commandName ^'archetype'`; spec
#     adds POSITIONAL `requestedArchetype description:
#     'Archetype you want to use'`)
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarBuildCommand.class.st lines
#     33-64 (`commandName ^'build'`; spec adds THREE
#     FLAGS — `addFlag: #templatable`, `addFlag: #all`,
#     `addFlag: #mainRoot` — and TWO POSITIONALS —
#     `#format` (description: 'The format you want pdf
#     is the default'), `#requestedFiles` with
#     `defaultValue: [ #('index.md') ]; multiple: true`)
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarServeCommand.class.st
#     lines 19-40 (`commandName ^'serve'`; spec adds
#     TWO POSITIONALS — `#baseurl defaultValue: ''`,
#     `#port defaultValue: [ 8080 ]` — and ONE FLAG
#     `addFlag: #watch`)
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarUpdateBuildCommand.class.st
#     lines 17-28 (`commandName ^ 'updateBuild'`; spec
#     has NO flags/positionals beyond addHelp)
#   src/Pillar-Cli/ClapPillarUpdateTemplateCommand.class.st
#     lines 17-29 (`commandName ^ 'updateTemplate'`;
#     spec adds POSITIONAL `requestedTemplate
#     description: 'Template you want to update'`)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# pillar is a **markup syntax and toolchain** for
# writing books, websites, and slides — Pharo's
# answer to Pandoc.  Pivots from R293 tawk (Tcl
# `cmdline::getoptions`) into the **Pharo Smalltalk
# language tooling cluster**.  Sister tools: Pharo
# (Smalltalk VM), Iceberg (Git client for Pharo),
# Metacello (package manager).  **MAJOR MILESTONE**:
# corpus's **first documented Pharo Smalltalk CLI** —
# adds Pharo Smalltalk `Clap` (port of Rust clap) to
# the cross-language CLI taxonomy (33 library variants
# now).
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **Pharo
# Smalltalk `Clap` library** at
# ClapPillarCommand.class.st:18 — a Smalltalk port of
# Rust's clap CLI library.  Spec is built via
# Smalltalk's **CASCADE MESSAGE chain** (semicolon
# `;`) — `(ClapCommandSpec id: #pillar) description:
# '...'; commandClass: self; addHelp; add: (ClapFlag
# id: #version); yourself` returns the receiver
# (`yourself`) at the END after configuring it via
# successive messages.  Documents the **cascade-chain
# builder pattern** — distinct from R277 Kotlin clikt
# (DSL receiver lambda), R278 Scala decline
# (combinator), and R276 Java picocli (annotations).
# Smalltalk cascades target the SAME RECEIVER for each
# `;`-separated message.  Corpus's **first documented
# Smalltalk cascade-chain CLI builder**.
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **auto-
# subcommand discovery via `allSubclasses`** at
# ClapPillarCommand.class.st:46-50 — `self
# pillarCommandsList do: [ :each | command
# addSubcommand: each ]` where `pillarCommandsList`
# returns `self allSubclasses select: [ :each | each
# isAbstract not ] thenCollect: [ :each | each
# commandSpecification ]`.  All concrete subclasses of
# `ClapPillarCommand` become subcommands AUTOMATICALLY
# — no manual registration.  Documents the **runtime-
# class-introspection subcommand discovery pattern**
# — distinct from R290 Racket explicit `#:subcommands`
# list, R276 picocli `@Command(subcommands = {...})`
# annotation array, R278 Scala decline `Opts.
# subcommand`, and R292 Erlang `main(["sub" | Argv])`
# pattern-match.  Smalltalk's `allSubclasses` walks
# the RUNTIME class hierarchy — adding a new
# subcommand is literally "create a new subclass that
# implements `commandName` and `commandSpecification`".
# Corpus's **first documented runtime-introspection
# subcommand discovery**.
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **Smalltalk
# class-side methods for spec definition** — `Cmd
# class >> commandSpecification` is the SPEC, `Cmd
# class >> commandName` is the NAME, and `Cmd >>
# execute` is the per-instance handler.  Distinct
# from R291 CL `defparameter *command-line-spec*`
# (global parameter), R290 Racket `multi-command-line`
# (macro), and R292 Erlang `-define(CONNECT_OPTS,
# ...)` (module-attribute macro).  Smalltalk's
# class-side methods are EQUIVALENT to static methods
# in other OO languages but with full reflective
# access to the metaclass.  The `<commandline>`
# pragma annotation on `commandSpecification` is the
# Smalltalk REGISTRATION HOOK — Clap scans for
# methods with this pragma to build the command tree.
# Documents the **pragma-annotated-class-method
# pattern** — distinct from Java `@Command`
# annotations on classes (R276 picocli) and Python
# `@click.command` decorators on functions (R266
# uvicorn).  Pragma is on the METHOD, the class is
# the unit of registration.
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **multi-value
# positional with default-list** at
# ClapPillarBuildCommand.class.st:58-62 —
# `addPositional: #requestedFiles spec: [
# :positional | positional description: '...';
# defaultValue: [ #('index.md') ]; multiple: true ]`.
# The `multiple: true` modifier makes this a
# VARIADIC positional (consumes ALL remaining argv).
# The `defaultValue:` block returns `#('index.md')`
# (Smalltalk LITERAL ARRAY syntax `#( ... )`) when
# no positional values are given.  Documents the
# **block-as-default + multiple-positional pattern**
# — distinct from R285 Lua argparse `:args("*")`
# string-count modifier and R276 picocli `@Parameters
# (arity = "0..*")`.  Smalltalk's default-as-BLOCK
# (`[ #('index.md') ]`) is LAZY — only evaluated when
# the positional is missing.  Corpus's **first
# documented lazy-block-default CLI positional**.
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **typed
# positionals with default conversion** at
# ClapPillarServeCommand.class.st:34-37/71-73 —
# `addPositional: #port spec: [ :positional |
# positional description: '...'; defaultValue: [
# 8080 ] ]` and at runtime `port := (self positional:
# #port) asInteger`.  The default value is a Smalltalk
# `SmallInteger` (8080) but the parsed CLI value
# arrives as a `String` — explicit `asInteger`
# conversion required.  Documents the **explicit-
# coerce-at-read pattern** — distinct from R292
# Erlang `getopt:parse` typed atoms (parser converts),
# R287 Nim `parseopt` `parseInt(p.val)` (caller
# converts), and R276 picocli `@Parameters(type =
# Integer.class)` (annotation-driven conversion).
# Smalltalk's late binding + dynamic typing means
# Clap does NOT pre-convert; the application calls
# `asInteger` / `asNumber` / `asFileReference` at
# the read site.  Corpus's **first documented
# explicit-coerce-at-read CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: pillar uses **`hasFlag:`
# at-runtime flag checks** at
# ClapPillarBuildCommand.class.st:73-75 — `(self
# hasFlag: #templatable) ifTrue: [ project
# beTemplatable ]`.  `hasFlag:` returns a Boolean and
# is checked via `ifTrue:` / `ifFalse:` blocks
# (Smalltalk's pattern-matched control flow on
# Boolean).  Documents the **`hasFlag:` Boolean-
# predicate-with-block dispatch pattern** —
# distinct from R285 Lua argparse table-field access
# (`args.verbose`), R290 Racket flag closures
# (`(*debug*)`), and R292 Erlang `proplists:
# get_bool(enable_ssl, NOpts)`.  Smalltalk's
# `ifTrue:` is itself a MESSAGE TO BOOLEAN — `true
# ifTrue: [ ... ]` evaluates the block, `false
# ifTrue: [ ... ]` does nothing.  Corpus's **first
# documented Boolean-message dispatch CLI**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped older `PR*CommandLineHandler`
# subclasses (legacy Pharo `CommandLineHandler`-based
# API; superseded by the `Clap*` classes in the same
# `Pillar-Cli` package).  Probed jvdsandt/pharo-aws-
# toolbox (AWS Lambda runtime, Pharo-internal), feenkcom
# /lepiter `LeHtmlBookExportCommandLineHandler`
# (lepiter is feenkcom's Pharo notebook tool — not a
# public CLI binary), GunterMueller/ST_STX_Fork
# (Smalltalk/X jupyter integration, niche), pharo-
# project/pharo-core various BasicCommandLineHandler
# subclasses (would conflict with `pharo` itself which
# is too generic and would dup with stock pharo
# binary), powerlang/egg `ParseResult` (library, not a
# CLI).  Chose pillar: complete Clap-based Pharo CLI,
# five subcommands with distinct surface (positional,
# flags, multi-positional, optional positional), and
# spec is built per-subcommand-class with
# `<commandline>` pragma — clean source-direct
# extraction surface.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

_arguments -C \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show pillar help]' \
  '--version[print the version of your Pharo VM]' \
  '1: :->subcommand' \
  '*:: :->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcommand)
    # Five subcommands decoded from
    # `commandName ^ '...'` of each
    # ClapPillar*Command class.
    local -a subcmds
    subcmds=(
      'archetype:create a pillar project with a basic template and skeleton files'
      'build:build pillar documents in the specified format'
      'serve:serve the current project over HTTP'
      'updateBuild:update build/archetypes using folder in parent directory'
      'updateTemplate:reinstall the given template'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'pillar subcommand' subcmds && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $line[1] in
      archetype)
        # ClapPillarArchetypeCommand line 27
        # (addPositional: #requestedArchetype).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show archetype help]' \
          '1:archetype name:(book article slides website)' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      build)
        # ClapPillarBuildCommand lines 45-62 (three
        # flags + two positionals — format & files).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show build help]' \
          '--templatable[use a template]' \
          '--all[build ALL pillar documents in repository]' \
          '--mainRoot[build only index.md in root directory (default strategy)]' \
          '1:output format (pdf is default):(pdf html markdown md latex tex epub beamer)' \
          '*:pillar files to build (default: index.md):_files -g "*.(md|pillar|markdown)"' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      serve)
        # ClapPillarServeCommand lines 30-38 (two
        # positionals: baseurl & port; one flag --watch).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show serve help]' \
          '--watch[watch source files and rebuild on change]' \
          '1:base URL (empty by default):' \
          '2:port (default: 8080):' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      updateBuild)
        # ClapPillarUpdateBuildCommand — no extra args.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show updateBuild help]' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      updateTemplate)
        # ClapPillarUpdateTemplateCommand line 28
        # (addPositional: #requestedTemplate).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show updateTemplate help]' \
          '1:template name:(book article slides website)' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
